user-favorite-trip.name: catacombs of kom el shuqafa
user-favorite-trip.title: Alexandria
user-favorite-trip.shortDescription: The catacombs of Kom El Shoqafa is a historical archaeological site located in Alexandria, Egypt, and is considered one of the Seven Wonders of the Middle Ages
user-favorite-trip.fullDescription: is a historical archaeological site located in Alexandria, Egypt, and is considered one of the Seven Wonders of the Middle Ages.The necropolis consists of a series of Alexandrian tombs, statues and archaeological objects of the Pharaonic funeral cult with Hellenistic and early Imperial Roman influences. Due to the time period, many of the features of the catacombs of Kom El Shoqafa merge Roman, Greek and Egyptian cultural points; some statues are Egyptian in style, yet bear Roman clothes and hair style whilst other features share a similar style. A circular staircase, which was often used to transport deceased bodies down the middle of it, leads down into the tombs that were tunneled into the bedrock during the age of the Antonine emperors (2nd century AD).The facility was then used as a burial chamber from the 2nd century to the 4th century, before being rediscovered in 1900 when a donkey accidentally fell into the access shaft. To date, three sarcophagi have been found, along with other human and animal remains which were added later. It is believed that the catacombs were only intended for a single family, but it is unclear why the site was expanded in order to house numerous other individuals.

tours.title: Alexandria
tours.name: Bibliotheca Alexandrina
tours.shortDescription: The Bibliotheca Alexandrina is a major library and cultural center located on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea in the Egyptian city of Alexandria
tours.fullDescription: is a major library and cultural center located on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea in the Egyptian city of Alexandria. It is both a commemoration of the Library of Alexandria that was lost in antiquity, and an attempt to rekindle something of the brilliance that this earlier center of study and erudition represented. The idea of reviving the old library dates back to 1974, when a committee set up by Alexandria University selected a plot of land for its new library.Construction work began in 1995 and, after some US$220 million had been spent, the complex was officially inaugurated on 16 October 2002.In 2010,the library received a donation of 500,000 books from the Bibliothèque nationale de France (BnF). The gift makes the Bibliotheca Alexandrina the sixth-largest Francophone library in the world.The library has shelf space for eight million books, with the main reading room covering 20,000 square metres (220,000 sq ft). The complex also houses a conference center; specialized libraries for maps, multimedia, the blind and visually impaired, young people, and for children; four museums; four art galleries for temporary exhibitions; 15 permanent exhibitions; a planetarium; and a manuscript restoration laboratory.

tours.title: Alexandria
tours.name: The Greco-Roman Museum
tours.shortDescription: The Graeco-Roman Museum is an archaeological museum located in Alexandria, Egypt. Erected in 1892, it was first built in a five-room apartment, inside one small building on Rosetta Street. In 1895, it was transferred to another
tours.fullDescription: The Greco-Roman Museum was officially opened on 17 October 1892 by Khedive Abbas Helmy the Second. Giuseppe Botti, an Italian, had undertaken the task of creating a museum in Alexandria dedicated to the Greco-Roman period.Interest in this period had begun in earnest after 1866, when Mahmoud El-Falaki completed his excavations in Alexandria, bringing to light the plan of the ancient city. Interest in the museum was enhanced by the formation of the Society of Archaeology in Alexandria in 1893.Initially, the collections were housed in part of a building situated in Rosetta Street, which is now El-Horreih Road. Construction of the first ten galleries of the present building was completed in 1895. The additional galleries (numbers 11 to 16) were completed in 1899 and the facade was completed in 1900. Some of the Greco-Roman artifacts, especially the coin collection, were obtained from the Bulaq Museum (now the Egyptian Museum) in Cairo.When Giuseppe Botti assumed responsibility for the management of the museum, he enriched it with collections obtained from his excavations in the city and its environs. When Evaristo Breccia and Achille Adriani subsequently took charge of the museum, they continued to supply it with objects from excavations in Alexandria. They also began to obtain artifacts for the museum from excavations in the Fayium region.The collections in the museum mostly date from the third century BC to the third century AD, spanning the Ptolemaic and Roman periods. The collections are categorized and organized in 27 rooms with some objects exhibited in the small garden.

tours.title: Alexandria
tours.name: pompey piilar
tours.shortDescription: Pompey's Pillar is a Roman triumphal column in Alexandria, Egypt, the largest of its type constructed outside the imperial capitals of Rome and Constantinople.
tours.fullDescription: is a Roman triumphal column in Alexandria, Egypt, the largest of its type constructed outside the imperial capitals of Rome and Constantinople,located at the Serapeum of Alexandria. The only known free-standing column in Roman Egypt which was not composed of drums, it is one of the largest ancient monoliths and one of the largest monolithic columns ever erected.

tours.name: The Royal Jewelry Museum
tours.title: Alexandria
tours.shortDescription: is an art and history museum in the Zizenia neighborhood of Alexandria, Egypt. It is located in the former palace of Princess Fatma Al-Zahra'. The building's halls contain an inestimable collection of jewels and jewelry of the Muhammad Ali Dynasty.
tours.fullDescription: is an art and history museum in the Zizenia neighborhood of Alexandria, Egypt. It is located in the former palace of Princess Fatma Al-Zahra'. The building's halls contain an inestimable collection of jewels and jewelry of the Muhammad Ali Dynasty. 19th-century paintings, statues, and decorative arts are also exhibited in the rooms and lobbies. The museum was first inaugurated on 24 October 1986. After several years of renovations and expansion it was reopened in April 2010.The museum houses major jewelry pieces and art acquisitions of the dynasty of Muhammad Ali and his descendants, who ruled Egypt for nearly 150 years from 1805 until the Egyptian Revolution of 1952. Following the Revolution, the jewelry left by the Royal Family was kept secure and unseen until a 1986 decree by President Mubarak was issued to assign Princess Fatima Al-Zahra' Palace in Alexandria as a special museum to house those pieces.

tours.name: El Montaza Palace
tours.title: Alexandria
tours.shortDescription: is a palace, museum and extensive gardens in the Montaza district of Alexandria, Egypt. It was built on a low plateau east of central Alexandria overlooking a beach on the Mediterranean Sea.
tours.fullDescription: The extensive Montaza Palace grounds first had the Salamlek Palace, built in 1892 by Khedive Abbas II, the last Muhammad Ali Dynasty ruler to hold the Khedive title over the Khedivate of Egypt and Sudan. It was used as a hunting lodge and residence for his companion.The larger Al-Haramlik Palace and royal gardens were added to the Montaza Palace grounds, being built by King Fuad I in 1932, as a summer palace. It is in a mixture of Ottoman and Florentine styles, with two towers. One of these towers rises distinctively high above with elaborated Italian Renaissance design details. The palace has long open arcades facing the sea along each floor.President Anwar El-Sadat renovated the original Salamlek Palace as an official presidential residence. It was most recently used by former president Hosni Mubarak.

tours.name: Citadel of Qaitbay
tours.title: Alexandria
tours.shortDescription: The Citadel of Qaitbay is a 15th-century defensive fortress located on the Mediterranean sea coast, in Alexandria, Egypt. It was established in 1477 AD by Sultan Al-Ashraf Sayf al-Din Qa'it Bay.
tours.fullDescription: is considered one of the most important defensive strongholds, not only in Egypt, but also along the Mediterranean Sea coast. It formulated an important part of the fortification system of Alexandria in the 15th century AD.The Citadel is situated at the entrance of the eastern harbour on the eastern point of the Pharos Island. It was erected on the exact site of the famous Lighthouse of Alexandria, which was one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World. The lighthouse continued to function until the time of the Arab conquest, then several disasters occurred and the shape of the lighthouse was changed to some extent, but it still continued to function. Restoration began in the period of Ahmed Ibn Tulun (about 880 AD). During the 11th century an earthquake occurred, causing damage to the octagonal part. The bottom survived, but it could only serve as a watchtower, and a small mosque was built on the top. In the 14th century there was a very destructive earthquake and the whole building was completely destroyed.

tours.name: Abu Simbel Tour
tours.title: Aswan
tours.shortDescription: The twin temples at Abu Simbel are 2 of the best-preserved and most awe-inspiring of ancient Egypt. Discover them with a quick and convenient plane ride from Aswan. See the towering statues of Ramesses II and his queen as you learn about their intriguing repositioning in the last century.
tours.fullDescription: The twin temples at Abu Simbel are 2 of the best-preserved and most awe-inspiring of ancient Egypt. Discover them with a quick and convenient plane ride from Aswan. See the towering statues of Ramesses II and his queen as you learn about their intriguing repositioning in the last century Enjoy a swift takeoff via plane from Aswan, then arrive close to the shores of Lake Nasser. Arriving at the temple site, marvel at the colossal statues guarding the entrances. Walk through the impressive façade into the Great Temple’s interior—images and carvings depicting ancient deities adorn the walls. Observe too the Small Temple, also hewn into the mountain-face that stands in honor to Queen Nefertari—Ramesses II’s chief consort

tours.name: Tour of Philae Temple
tours.title: Aswan
tours.shortDescription: Venture into Aswan's most important sites on this tailor-made tour designed uniquely to your preferences. Enjoy a scenic motorboat trip on the Nile, explore the Temple of Philae dedicated to the Goddess Isis, see the largest obelisk known on earth, and marvel at the Aswan High Dam.
tours.fullDescription: Your tour begins with a walk across the High Dam, which was constructed between 1960 and 1970 to separate Lake Nasser from the Nile River. Hear why this powerful embankment dam became a key objective of the Egyptian government in 1952, mainly to control the floods that used to happen every year during late summer. Next, board a motorboat and enjoy a scenic ride on the river Nile to Lake Nasser and Agilkia Island, which has been shaped to match the size of the magnificent Philae Temple. Your guide explains how a UNESCO project in 1960 saved the Temple of Philae from flooding and moved it to the nearby island of Agilkia, where it still stands today.

tours.name: Kalabsha Temple
tours.title: Aswan
tours.shortDescription: Spend your day exploring 2 of the most important complexes in Nubia with the help of your private guide. You visit the Temple of Kalabsha, the largest freestanding temple in the region, and Nubian Museum.
tours.fullDescription: Venture into the history of Egypt's Nubia region and learn of the impact of the Aswan High Dam on the area. First, indulge in the views of the Nile as you take a motorboat to the ancient Temple of Kalabsha, set on the banks of Lake Nasser. The temple itself was built by the Roman emperor Octavius Augustus in 30 BC as a tribute to Mandulis (Merul), a Lower Nubian sun god. Explore the largest freestanding temple in Egyptian Nubia and admire a fine carving of Horus emerging from reeds on its inner curtain wall. Follow your guide, who shows you its most remarkable carvings and features, and see why the temple is considered one of the most complete in the region. Then, visit the International Museum of Nubia, a result of UNESCO's initiative to preserve artifacts from the area's history.

tours.name: tour to Pyramids
tours.title: Cairo
tours.shortDescription: Traveling to Cairo without seeing the Great Pyramids of Giza and infamous Sphinx is like traveling to Paris without making a stop at the Eiffel Tower
tours.fullDescription: Traveling to Cairo without seeing the Great Pyramids of Giza and infamous Sphinx is like traveling to Paris without making a stop at the Eiffel Tower. Experience the best of this incredible and ancient city on a private tour of Cairo. Follow your own Egyptologist through all the highlights and enjoy personalized attention as your tour the city’s most iconic destinations. The flexibility of a private tour means you can decide how much time to spend at each of the sites, insuring a truly memorable experience

tours.name: Al-Azhar Mosque
tours.title: Cairo
tours.shortDescription: Al-Azhar Mosque is the finest building of Cairo's Fatimid era and one of the city's earliest surviving mosques, completed in AD 972.
tours.fullDescription: Al-Azhar Mosque is the finest building of Cairo's Fatimid era and one of the city's earliest surviving mosques, completed in AD 972. It's also one of the world's oldest universities — Caliph El-Aziz bestowed it with the status of university in AD 988 (the other university vying for oldest status is in Fes and today, Al-Azhar University is still the leading theological center of the Islamic world.

tours.name: Old Cairo
tours.title: Cairo
tours.shortDescription: This small church-filled cluster of twisty laneways lies within the walls of Old Babylon where the Roman Emperor Trajan first built a fortress along the Nile
tours.fullDescription: This small church-filled cluster of twisty laneways lies within the walls of Old Babylon where the Roman Emperor Trajan first built a fortress along the Nile. Parts of the Roman towers still preside over the main street.

tours.name: The Citadel
tours.title: Cairo
tours.shortDescription: In a commanding location at the foot of the Mokattam Hills, Cairo's citadel was built by Saladin in 1176.
tours.fullDescription: In a commanding location at the foot of the Mokattam Hills, Cairo's citadel was built by Saladin in 1176. The original structure he laid out has long disappeared except for the eastern outer walls, but a legacy of rulers has made their own additions here.

tours.name: El Nabatat Island
tours.title: Aswan
tours.shortDescription: Geziret En Nabatat (Plant Island) or the Botanical Island is a small, oval-shaped island in the Nile at Aswan
tours.fullDescription: Geziret En Nabatat (Plant Island) or the Botanical Island is a small, oval-shaped island in the Nile at Aswan, it was previously known as Kitchener's Island, named after Lord Kitchener who owned it as he was gifted the island, when he served as Consul-General in Egypt.

tours.name: Mausoleum of Aga Khan
tours.title: Aswan
tours.shortDescription: The Mausoleum of Aga Khan is the mausoleum of Aga Khan III, Sir Sultan Muhammed Shah, who died in 1957.
tours.fullDescription: The Mausoleum of Aga Khan is the mausoleum of Aga Khan III, Sir Sultan Muhammed Shah, who died in 1957. The mausoleum is located at Aswan, along the Nile of Egypt, since Egypt was formerly the centre of power of the Fatimids. The mausoleum is built in the style of the Fatimid tombs in Cairo.

tours.name: Agilkia Island
tours.title: Aswan
tours.shortDescription: An island in the reservoir of the Old Aswan Dam along the Nile River in southern Egypt; it is the present site of the relocated Ancient Egyptian temple complex of Philae. Agilkia,
tours.fullDescription: An island in the reservoir of the Old Aswan Dam along the Nile River in southern Egypt; it is the present site of the relocated Ancient Egyptian temple complex of Philae. Agilkia, like the island, was the name chosen for the planned landing site on a comet by the Rosetta spacecraft mission's Philae lander.

restaurants.title: Cairo
restaurants.name: Abu Tarek
restaurants.shortDescription: We have no other branches!’ proclaims this temple of kushari
restaurants.fullDescription: ‘We have no other branches!’ proclaims this temple of kushari (mix of noodles, rice, black lentils, fried onions and tomato sauce). No, the place has just expanded, decade by decade, into the upper storeys of its building, and continues to hold on to Cairo's unofficial 'best kushari' title. Eat in, rather than takeaway, to check out the elaborate decor upstairs.

restaurants.title: Cairo
restaurants.name: Zööba
restaurants.shortDescription: Egyptian street food gets a modern makeover. Zööba has taken the country's classic cheap eats and given them contemporary twists.
restaurants.fullDescription: Egyptian street food gets a modern makeover. Zööba has taken the country's classic cheap eats and given them contemporary twists. Whole-grain kushari (mix of noodles, rice, black lentils, fried onions and tomato sauce), beetroot baladi bread, pickled lemon and spicy pepper ta'amiyya sandwiches, and some seriously good salads and shawarma. Eat in at the zinc-clad table amid the most eclectic of decors, or take out – this is ideal picnic fodder

restaurants.title: Cairo
restaurants.name: Kebabgy
restaurants.shortDescription: Excellent Egyptian restaurant with a stylish interior room and a fabulous Nile terrace, serving fancy succulent kebabs and kofta as well as excellent mezze.
restaurants.fullDescription: Excellent Egyptian restaurant with a stylish interior room and a fabulous Nile terrace, serving fancy succulent kebabs and kofta as well as excellent mezze.

restaurants.title: Aswan
restaurants.name: Nubian Beach
restaurants.shortDescription: Nubian cafe-restaurant set in a quiet garden on the west bank of the Nile
restaurants.fullDescription: Nubian cafe-restaurant set in a quiet garden on the west bank of the Nile, against the backdrop of a towering sand dune and near a popular swimming spot. When it's too hot or on colder evenings, you can also chill out in its beautifully painted indoor room. The food is simple but good, and beer is sometimes served.

restaurants.title: Aswan
restaurants.name: Nubian Dream
restaurants.shortDescription: It is a Nubian restaurant in Aswan where you will get the opportunity to taste the authentic Egyptian cuisine.
restaurants.fullDescription: It is a Nubian restaurant in Aswan where you will get the opportunity to taste the authentic Egyptian cuisine. The place is located in a Nubian village on an island and you would need a boat ride. The food is so delicious that most tourists come back here again and again on their holiday and you will too. The best thing is it is open till late in the night. So, if you want to grab a late dinner, you know where to come. The staff is polite and generous too. Enjoy the beautiful views of the Nile from the windows of the restaurant.

restaurants.title: Aswan
restaurants.name: Panorama
restaurants.shortDescription: Panorama Restaurant in Aswan is a must-visit place if you want to relish delectable Egyptian Cuisine. The restaurant is located on Elephantine Island
restaurants.fullDescription: Panorama Restaurant in Aswan is a must-visit place if you want to relish delectable Egyptian Cuisine. The restaurant is located on Elephantine Island and offers breathtaking views of Nile from the 13th floor. It is an amazing place to enjoy a romantic sunset dinner. Could there be a better way to end your night with your spouse? We think not. Try the mouthwatering dishes from their menu. The ambiance is fantastic and the staff is attentive and courteous.

restaurants.title: Aswan
restaurants.name: 1902 Restaurant
restaurants.shortDescription: If you have had enough of Egyptian food, come to 1902 restaurant in Aswan to enjoy continental cuisine. 1902 is known for its fine dining experience and amazing French
restaurants.fullDescription: If you have had enough of Egyptian food, come to 1902 restaurant in Aswan to enjoy continental cuisine. 1902 is known for its fine dining experience and amazing French, European, and international cuisine. You will fall in love, not with just the food but also the elegant setting of the restaurant. The quiet ambiance of this restaurant is perfect for planning a dinner date. So, if you are on your honeymoon in Egypt, you know where to dine. In fact, put dining at this restaurant as one of the things to do in Aswan.

restaurants.title: Cairo
restaurants.name: Sequoia, Zamalek
restaurants.shortDescription: The great vibes and stunning view of this place is still unmatched anywhere else in the city. You’re basically surrounded by the Nile from all angles.
restaurants.fullDescription: The great vibes and stunning view of this place is still unmatched anywhere else in the city. You’re basically surrounded by the Nile from all angles. Their menu is very diverse and they serve alcoholic beverages and shisha.

restaurants.title: Cairo
restaurants.name: Andrea, New Giza
restaurants.shortDescription: This is a personal favourite of mine. It takes after the famous Marryoteya one and the food is to die for. The grilled chicken
restaurants.fullDescription: This is a personal favourite of mine. It takes after the famous Marryoteya one and the food is to die for. The grilled chicken, chicken liver and Kobeba are a must try! You can get your name customized in a sand bottle, watch your bread being baked the old-school way over the coals or take a donkey ride. Yes, you read that right.

restaurants.title: Cairo
restaurants.name: Tabla LUNA, Maadi
restaurants.shortDescription: This Maadi restaurant features colourful, vibrant interiors with Aztec and Mayan inspired floor tiles. It is the first Latin American restaurant of its kind in Egypt
restaurants.fullDescription: This Maadi restaurant features colourful, vibrant interiors with Aztec and Mayan inspired floor tiles. It is the first Latin American restaurant of its kind in Egypt. Tabla LUNA has established itself in Cairo for its very creative and super delicious dishes. There’s nowhere else in Cairo where you can get a mango filled with white chocolate flan.

hotels.name: Four Seasons
hotels.title: Alexandria
hotels.shortDescription: Set on a busy roundabout, this low-key hotel is 1 km from the nearest beach, 2 km from the Citadel of Qaitbay
hotels.fullDescription: Set on a busy roundabout, this low-key hotel is 1 km from the nearest beach, 2 km from the Citadel of Qaitbay, a 15th-century seafront fortress, and 9 km from Alexandria International Airport.The straightforward rooms have wood floors and balconies, and offer Wi-Fi access, flat-screen TVs and minibars. Some have sitting areas.Amenities include an airy restaurant, and a down-to-earth cafe featuring outdoor seating.

hotels.name: Amoun Hotel
hotels.title: Alexandria
hotels.shortDescription: Set on a busy roundabout, this low-key hotel is 1 km from the nearest beach, 2 km from the Citadel of Qaitbay

hotels.name: Hilton Green Plaza
hotels.title: Alexandria
hotels.shortDescription: Set 3 km from Alexandria International Airport, this polished hotel in the Green Plaza shopping mall is 5 km from the Royal Jewelry Museum Refined rooms feature flat-screen TVs, seating areas and Wi-Fi, plus tea and coffeemakers.
hotels.fullDescription: Set 3 km from Alexandria International Airport, this polished hotel in the Green Plaza shopping mall is 5 km from the Royal Jewelry Museum Refined rooms feature flat-screen TVs, seating areas and Wi-Fi, plus tea and coffeemakers. Club rooms and suites add access to a lounge with complimentary breakfast and drinks. Suites also have living areas. Room service is available Amenities consist of a spa, indoor and an outdoor pools, a gym and a game room. There are multiple bars and dining options, including Indian and Italian restaurants. Event space is offered. Parking is available (fee).

hotels.name: TOLIP Hotel
hotels.title: Alexandria
hotels.shortDescription: Across the street from a beach on the Mediterranean Sea, this refined hotel with a colorful facade is 6 km from the Alexandria National Museum and 5 km from Green Plaza Mall.Sophisticated rooms feature free Wi-Fi, flat-screen TVs, minifridges and balconies; some rooms offer sea views.
hotels.fullDescription: Across the street from a beach on the Mediterranean Sea, this refined hotel with a colorful facade is 6 km from the Alexandria National Museum and 5 km from Green Plaza Mall.Sophisticated rooms feature free Wi-Fi, flat-screen TVs, minifridges and balconies; some rooms offer sea views. Suites add living rooms and dining tables.Breakfast is complimentary. There are 6 restaurants (1 offering Italian fare). Other amenities include a fitness center, a chic spa, a private beach, and a courtyard with a seasonal outdoor pool. Parking is extra.

hotels.name: Steigenberger Cecil
hotels.title: Cairo
hotels.shortDescription: Across the road from the Al Mina' ash Sharqiyah harbor, this elegant hotel dating from 1929 overlooks the Corniche waterfront promenade and the Mediterranean Sea. It's a 2-minute walk from the Caesareum of Alexandria, an ancient temple, and a 4-minute walk from El Raml train station.
hotels.fullDescription: Across the road from the Al Mina' ash Sharqiyah harbor, this elegant hotel dating from 1929 overlooks the Corniche waterfront promenade and the Mediterranean Sea. It's a 2-minute walk from the Caesareum of Alexandria, an ancient temple, and a 4-minute walk from El Raml train station.The traditionally and warmly decorated rooms feature balconies, free Wi-Fi and flat-screens, plus tea and coffeemakers. Suites offer living rooms.

hotels.name: Sofitel Legend Old Cataract
hotels.title: Aswan
hotels.shortDescription: Located in the Nubian Desert on the banks of the Nile, opposite Elephantine Island, Sofitel Legend Old Cataract offers elegant rooms and suites. It features outdoor and indoor pools.

hotels.name: Philae Hotel Aswan
hotels.title: Aswan
hotels.shortDescription: Situated along the stretch of the Corniche El Nile, Philae Hotel is located in Aswan. It offers air-conditioned accommodation with balconies overlooking the Nile. It features free Wi-Fi in all area and a restaurant that serves American Breakfast.

hotels.name: Fairmont Nile City
hotels.title: Cairo
hotels.shortDescription: Located in the Nile City Towers by the River Nile, this 5-star hotel features a rooftop pool deck with spectacular views across Cairo to the Pyramids. It offers 7 food and beverage venues.

hotels.name: Sofitel Nile El Gezirah
hotels.title: Cairo
hotels.shortDescription: Sofitel El Gezirah is a 5-star luxury hotel with a private promenade along the Nile. Located in the city centre, it is within walking distance to the Opera House and Cairo Tower, as well as the Egyptian Museum and Khan El Khalili. It features an infinity outdoor pool.

hotels.name: Valencia Hotel
hotels.title: Cairo
hotels.shortDescription: Set within 600 m from The Egyptian Museum in Cairo, Valencia Hotel offers air-conditioned rooms with free Wi-Fi and views of the city. There is a bar and a shared lounge.

hotels.name: Al Masa Hotel
hotels.title: Cairo
hotels.shortDescription: Al Masah Hotel and Spa features a terrace with a swimming pool. Located in the green area of Nasr City, it offers 5 restaurants and a wellness centre. All the elegant rooms have a balcony.

hotels.name: Bet El Kerem
hotels.title: Aswan
hotels.shortDescription: Located in front of the Tombs of the Nobles in Aswan, Bet El Kerem offers rooms with air conditioning. Its rooftop terrace has panoramic views of the desert and the Nile.

travelPlan.fullDisc: Start your adventure visiting Opera house, Cairo Tower. travelPlan.fullDisc: At the First Visit the High Dam, Unfinished Obelisk. After that you’ll be moving to the Great Nubian temples of Philae. visite Kom Ombo and Edfu Temples, Then sail to Edfu. and Sail to Luxor late arrival, Visit Karnak and Luxor Temple. next visite Valley of the Kings, Temple of Queen Hatshepsut at El Deir El Bahary and the Colossi of Memnon.

At the end, head to the Montaza Gardens to see the Al-Haramlik Palace.

At the end, head to the Montaza Gardens to see the Al-Haramlik Palace.

travelPlan.fullDisc: Start your adventure visiting Opera house, Cairo Tower. Cross the bridge that connects Cairo with Giza to dive into the downtown and browse Tahrir Square,Explore Cairo's old gates, walk through Al Moez street, the largest open-air museum of Islamic architecture in the world.End your tour at the famous old bazaar of Khan El Khalili.
